description:
6pm to 6am curfew set by government; 

adapted on March 30 to 2pm to 7am and work hours limited from 9.00-12.00

March 21, 2020: 
Nationwide curfew imposed. The Libyan Presidential Council of the Government of National Accord (GNA) has announced a curfew across Libya starting March 22 from 6.00 p.m. to 6.00 a.m. The curfew excluded security, health workers and other people involved in pharmacy services, environmental work, energy, telecommunications and cargo.
On March 22, the High Committee against the Corona Virus imposes a curfew from 6:00 PM to 6:00 AM.
enforcer: Other (Please specify in the text box)

description:
On March 22, 2020, Libya declared country-wide curfew, which ""is from 6pm until 6am,"" closing ""all mosques at all prayer times, educational institutions, cafes, restaurants, events halls, clubs, entertainment centres and commercial outlets"" during curfew hours.

The decree also states that ""curfew breakers will be liable to punishment under existing laws.""
Libya’s eastern-based government impose a 24-hour curfew to fight any possible COVID-19 infections.
compliance: Mandatory with Exceptions (Please list exceptions in the text entry)

description: In Libya, it was announced on March 23 that ""a daily curfew from 3 p.m. until 7 a.m. in all areas under the control of the LAAF. These include eastern cities, the city of Sebha in the south, and Sebratha on the western coast""

In Libya, it was announced on March 23 that ""a daily curfew from 3 p.m. until 7 a.m. in all areas under the control of the LAAF. These include eastern cities, the city of Sebha in the south, and Sebratha on the western coast""

On April 20, it was announced by the Fuel Crisis Committee that drivers for fuel distribution centers and drivers of trucks delivering LPG bottled gas cylinders will be exempted from the curfew.
The Misrata Municipality reduced the curfew in its administrative boundaries from 02:00 PM to 07:00 AM.
Libya enforces a total curfew on all its citizens except essential workers.
compliance: Mandatory with Exceptions (Please list exceptions in the text entry)

description: On March 15th, 2020, Libya declares a state of emergency and allocates half a billion dinars (approximately $352 221 633) to face the pandemic.
On March 16,2020 both the internationally recognised government in Tripoli, in the west, and a rival administration ruling from Benghazi in the east have declared emergency.
On March 15, Libya's UN-recognized Government of National Accord (GNA) suspended all flights at the Misrata Airport for three weeks.
On Monday, March 16th, Libya's UN-recognized Government of National Accord (GNA) suspended all flights at the Misrata Airport for three weeks.

description: On March 23, 2020, the Ministry of Health declared that it is"" in the process of establishing centers in a number of regions to house any suspected cases of coronavirus."" Additionally, medical teams are ""undergoing training in cooperation with international organizations prior to their deployment to the centers dedicated to Covid-19 patients.""

The ministry has ""prepared 16 health isolation sites outside hospitals and is preparing 500 beds for intensive care units."" Additionally, the Minister will also ""start a mobile clinic to conduct checkups and tests at home.""

on March 30, 2020, The Ministry of Health said ""it had distributed around 50 sterilization and ambulance cars to several municipalities, but did not specify the cities that will receive this equipment.""
In Libya, The National Center for Disease Control continues to create rapid response teams for COVID cases.
enforcer: National Government,Other (Please specify in the text box)

description:
On May 27, 2020, A COVID-19 Rapid Response Centre has been established in Tripoli, which will be staffed by 40 doctors and 20 consultants to respond to incoming calls. The centre will be linked to all 19 established isolation and hospitalization sites and will
coordinate its work with 65 Rapid Response Teams and almost 600 health professionals.

description: On March 30, 2020, the Ministry of Health imported 150 ventilators.

On July 12, 2020, Libya's Ministry of Education Covid-19 sent out protective kits to schools in each district incase schools reopen. 

These kits include more than 7 million masks as well as gloves, in addition to thousands of devices related to temperature measuring and sterilization materials.

description:
On July 29, 2020, The Presidential Council (PC), made a decision to establish a Preventive Medicine Hospital inside the Isolation Center at the Mitiga base in Tripoli.

The ministry said that the Preventive Medicine Hospital will have a capacity of 100 beds and will be affiliated with the Ministry of Health

On August 4, 2020, The Ministry of Health has raised the clinical capacity of the Souq Tolata Isolation Centre in Tripoli to 100 beds, having been supported by Swiss mobile medical units, equipped with specialised biological filter technology, air conditioning and kitted out with toilet facilities.

The Health Ministry had equipped one of Nalut Central Hospital buildings to operate as an isolation centre with a capacity of 80 beds.

The new isolation site includes 16 intensive care beds and is provided with monitoring systems, examination rooms, and a place for the medical staff.
On August 5, the Libyan health ministry confirmed the completion of another isolation site in Gharyan city, with a capacity of 82 beds, including 12 intensive care beds.

On August 5, the Libyan Health Minister announced that it has equipped the center located at one of Gharyan Teaching Hospital buildings with an oxygen system as well as other facilities required to begin operations as an isolation centre.

The Misarata Branch of The National Center for Disease Control is opening a laboratory that examines laboratory samples, the most prominent of which is the detection samples of the emerging corona virus.
enforcer: Other (Please specify in the text box)

description:
In Libya on April 21, 2020, ""The Deputy Foreign Minister of the internationally recognized Libyan government based in Tripoli, Mahmoud Al-Tilisi, said yesterday that the committee formed to repatriate Libyans stranded abroad as a result of border closures to mitigate the spread of the Coronavirus (Covid-19) had started the repatriation process.""

""committee began its work by reaching out to Libyan consulates and heads of missions and embassies abroad to provide the necessary health care as well as accommodation and subsistence services for stranded citizens.""

""work of the committee is divided into two phases. The first phase of this process includes the provision of housing for quarantine and health care and subsistence services. The second phase includes real-time PCR (polymerise chain reaction) detection procedures, as well as quarantine procedures.""

description:
The Libyan Interior Ministry's Coronavirus task force announced a lockdown during the Eid Al-Fitr days. 

The Interior Ministry urged the residents not to go out except for necessities and to abide by cooperation with the relevant authorities to preserve their safety, instructing security apparatuses to fine and take legal procedures against the violators. Libya will see 24-hour lockdown on the three days of Eid Al-Fitr from Sunday to Tuesday.
